SIMPLE: upland
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Upland
<hw>Up"land</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>High land;
ground elevated above the meadows and intervals which lie on the banks
of rivers, near the sea, or between hills; land which is generally dry;
-- opposed to <contr>lowland</contr>, <contr>meadow</contr>,
<contr>marsh</contr>, <contr>swamp</contr>, <contr>interval</contr>, and
the like.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The country, as distinguished from the neighborhood
of towns.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Upland</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Upland
<hw>Up"land</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to
uplands; being on upland; high in situation; <as>as, <ex>upland</ex>
inhabitants; <ex>upland</ex> pasturage</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sometimes, with secure delight⟦br⟧
The <qex>upland</qex> hamlets will invite.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Pertaining to the country, as distinguished from the
neighborhood of towns; rustic; rude; unpolished.</def>
<mark>[Obs.W2]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧ The race of <xex>upland</xex>
giants.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Chapman.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Upland moccasin</b></col>. <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <cd>See
<er>Moccasin</er>.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Upland sandpiper</b></col>,
<it>or</it> <col><b>Upland plover</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>,
<cd>a large American sandpiper (<spn>Bartramia longicauda</spn>) much
valued as a game bird. Unlike most sandpipers, it frequents fields and
uplands. Called also <altname>Bartramian sandpiper</altname>,
<altname>Bartram's tattler</altname>, <altname>field plover</altname>,
<altname>grass plover</altname>, <altname>highland plover</altname>,
<altname>hillbird</altname>, <altname>humility</altname>,
<altname>prairie plover</altname>, <altname>prairie pigeon</altname>,
<altname>prairie snipe</altname>, <altname>papabote</altname>,
<altname>quaily</altname>, and <altname>uplander</altname>.</cd> --
<col><b>Upland sumach</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a North American
shrub of the genus Rhus (<spn>Rhus glabra</spn>), used in tanning and
dyeing.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Uplander</ent>⟦br⟧
